  "prompt": "Is the Tamil language older than Sanskrit? How old is it when compared to all other languages of the world?",
  "response": "The question of whether Tamil is older than Sanskrit is complex and often debated among linguists and historians, as the \"age\" of a language can be interpreted in different ways.\n\n### Tamil and Sanskrit: A Comparative Perspective\n1. **Tamil**:  \n   Tamil is one of the oldest living languages in the world and is classified as a Dravidian language. The earliest written records of Tamil date back to the 3rd century BCE (Tamil-Brahmi inscriptions), and the language has a continuous literary tradition since the Sangam period (circa 300 BCE to 300 CE). Tamil is still widely spoken today, particularly in the Indian state of Tamil Nadu and Sri Lanka.\n\n2. **Sanskrit**:  \n   Sanskrit, on the other hand, is an Indo-Aryan language and is considered the liturgical and scholarly language of ancient India. The earliest form of Sanskrit, known as Vedic Sanskrit, dates back to the second millennium BCE (circa 1500\u20131200 BCE), as found in the Rigveda. Classical Sanskrit, codified by Panini around 500 BCE, became the language of literature, philosophy, and science in ancient India. Sanskrit is no longer a spoken language in its classical form but remains influential.\n\n### Age of Tamil Compared to Other Languages\nTamil is among the older languages still in use today. However, it is not the oldest language in the world. Some of the oldest recorded languages include:\n- **Sumerian** (circa 3100 BCE): The earliest written records in Mesopotamia.\n- **Egyptian** (circa 3000 BCE): Hieroglyphic inscriptions from ancient Egypt.\n- **Akkadian** (circa 2500 BCE): A Semitic language used in ancient Mesopotamia.\n- **Chinese** (circa 1200 BCE): Oracle bone script from the Shang dynasty.\n\nWhile Tamil may not be as old as Sumerian or Egyptian, it is one of the oldest continuously used languages with a rich literary tradition.\n\n### Conclusion\nTamil is older than Classical Sanskrit but younger than Vedic Sanskrit. It is one of the oldest living languages in the world, with a history spanning over two millennia. However, it is not the oldest language globally, as languages like Sumerian and Egyptian predate it. The age of a language is often measured by its earliest written records, and Tamil's literary heritage places it among the most ancient languages still in active use today.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
